      <!-- ── Quick Start ── -->
      <section id="quickstart">
        <h2>Quick Start</h2>
        <p>ForgeLite is a minimal, self-hostable Git hosting platform. It requires <strong>Node.js 22+</strong> (uses the built-in <code>node:sqlite</code> — no native dependencies) and <strong>Git</strong> installed on the server.</p>

        <h3>Installation</h3>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/3289david/forgelite.git
cd forgelite
npm install
cp .env.example .env</code></pre>

        <p>Edit <code>.env</code> and set a strong <code>JWT_SECRET</code>. Then start:</p>
        <pre><code># Development (hot reload)
npm run dev

# Production
npm run build && npm start</code></pre>

        <p>Open <a href="http://localhost:3000">http://localhost:3000</a>, register an account, and create your first repository.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Configuration ── -->
      <section id="config">
        <h2>Configuration</h2>
        <p>All configuration is via environment variables (or a <code>.env</code> file in the project root).</p>
        <table class="docs-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Variable</th><th>Default</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>PORT</code></td><td><code>3000</code></td><td>Port the server listens on</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>HOST</code></td><td><code>0.0.0.0</code></td><td>Bind address</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>JWT_SECRET</code></td><td><code>change-me</code></td><td><strong>Required in production.</strong> Long random string used to sign session tokens.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>DATA_DIR</code></td><td><code>./data</code></td><td>Directory where the SQLite database and bare git repositories are stored</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>BASE_URL</code></td><td><code>http://localhost:3000</code></td><td>Publicly accessible URL — used in clone URLs shown in the UI</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="docs-callout"><strong>Security:</strong> Always set a long random <code>JWT_SECRET</code> in production. Use <code>openssl rand -hex 32</code> to generate one.</div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Clone & Push ── -->
      <section id="clone">
        <h2>Clone &amp; Push</h2>
        <p>ForgeLite implements the full <strong>Git HTTP smart protocol</strong> using <code>git http-backend</code>. All standard git operations work out of the box.</p>

        <h3>Clone a repository</h3>
        <pre><code>git clone http://localhost:3000/username/repo-name.git

# Or with credentials inline
git clone http://username:password@localhost:3000/username/repo-name.git</code></pre>

        <h3>Push to a repository</h3>
        <pre><code># First push (new branch)
git push http://username:password@localhost:3000/username/repo.git main

# Subsequent pushes (after setting remote)
git remote add origin http://username:password@localhost:3000/username/repo.git
git push origin main</code></pre>

        <h3>Pull changes</h3>
        <pre><code>git pull http://username:password@localhost:3000/username/repo.git main</code></pre>

        <h3>Clone URL format</h3>
        <pre><code>http://[username:password@]host/owner/repo-name.git</code></pre>
        <p>The <code>.git</code> suffix is required. Omitting it will return the web UI page instead.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Auth ── -->
      <section id="auth">
        <h2>Authentication</h2>
        <p>ForgeLite supports two authentication methods for git CLI operations:</p>

        <h3>Password authentication</h3>
        <p>Use your ForgeLite username and account password directly in the git URL or when prompted:</p>
        <pre><code>git clone http://alice:mypassword@localhost:3000/alice/myrepo.git</code></pre>

        <h3>Personal Access Tokens</h3>
        <p>Tokens are more secure than passwords — they can be revoked without changing your account password and are ideal for scripts and CI environments.</p>
        <pre><code># Use token as the password
git clone http://alice:flt_abc123...@localhost:3000/alice/myrepo.git</code></pre>
        <p>Generate tokens in <strong>Repository Settings → Access Tokens</strong>. Tokens start with <code>flt_</code> and are shown only once at creation time.</p>

        <h3>Storing credentials with git</h3>
        <pre><code># Store credentials in macOS Keychain
git config --global credential.helper osxkeychain

# Store credentials in a file (Linux)
git config --global credential.helper store

# Then clone once — git will remember the credentials
git clone http://alice@localhost:3000/alice/myrepo.git</code></pre>

        <h3>Public repositories</h3>
        <p>Public repositories can be cloned and fetched without any credentials. Pushing always requires authentication.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Tokens ── -->
      <section id="tokens">
        <h2>Personal Access Tokens</h2>
        <p>Personal Access Tokens (PATs) are the recommended way to authenticate git CLI operations in scripts, CI, and automation.</p>

        <h3>Creating a token</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Open any repository you own and go to <strong>Settings</strong></li>
          <li>Scroll to <strong>Access Tokens</strong></li>
          <li>Enter a descriptive name (e.g., <code>laptop</code>, <code>ci-deploy</code>) and click <strong>Generate token</strong></li>
          <li>Copy the token immediately — it is shown only once</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="docs-callout"><strong>Important:</strong> Store the token securely. If you lose it, revoke it and create a new one. ForgeLite only stores a hash of the token and cannot retrieve the original value.</div>

        <h3>Using a token</h3>
        <pre><code># In git URL
git clone http://alice:flt_yourtokenhere@localhost:3000/alice/repo.git

# As environment variable (safer for scripts)
GIT_ASKPASS="echo flt_yourtokenhere" git clone http://alice@localhost:3000/alice/repo.git</code></pre>

        <h3>Revoking a token</h3>
        <p>Go to <strong>Repository Settings → Access Tokens</strong> and click <strong>Revoke</strong> next to the token you want to remove.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Repositories ── -->
      <section id="repos">
        <h2>Repositories</h2>
        <p>Repositories are the core of ForgeLite. Each repository is stored as a bare git repo on disk at <code>DATA_DIR/repos/owner/repo-name.git</code>.</p>

        <h3>Creating a repository</h3>
        <p>Click <strong>+ New</strong> in the navbar or go to <a href="/new">/new</a>. Choose a name, optional description, and whether it's public or private.</p>

        <h3>Forking</h3>
        <p>Click the <strong>Fork</strong> button on any public repository to create your own copy. The fork is a full clone — you can push to it independently.</p>

        <h3>Starring</h3>
        <p>Star repositories to bookmark them. Star counts are visible on repository cards.</p>

        <h3>Visibility</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Public</strong> — anyone can view and clone</li>
          <li><strong>Private</strong> — only the owner can view, clone, or push</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Change visibility in <strong>Repository → Settings</strong>.</p>

        <h3>Deleting a repository</h3>
        <p>Go to <strong>Repository → Settings → Danger Zone</strong>. Type the repository name to confirm deletion. This permanently removes the git data and all issues/PRs from the database.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Issues ── -->
      <section id="issues">
        <h2>Issues</h2>
        <p>Issues track bugs, feature requests, and tasks. Any user can open an issue on a public repository.</p>

        <h3>Opening an issue</h3>
        <p>Go to <strong>Repository → Issues → New issue</strong>. Fill in a title and optional Markdown body.</p>

        <h3>Comments</h3>
        <p>Anyone signed in can comment on an issue. Comments support full Markdown including code blocks.</p>

        <h3>Closing and reopening</h3>
        <p>The issue author or repository owner can close or reopen an issue using the button below the comment form.</p>

        <h3>Markdown in issues</h3>
        <pre><code>## Bug description
The widget crashes when clicking **Submit**.

### Steps to reproduce
1. Open the form
2. Click Submit without filling required fields

### Expected behavior
Show a validation error.

```js
// Example code
submitForm()
```</code></pre>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Pull Requests ── -->
      <section id="prs">
        <h2>Pull Requests</h2>
        <p>Pull requests let you propose changes from one branch and merge them into another. ForgeLite uses real <code>git merge</code> under the hood.</p>

        <h3>Creating a pull request</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Push your feature branch to the repository</li>
          <li>Go to <strong>Repository → Pull Requests → New pull request</strong></li>
          <li>Select the <strong>base branch</strong> (merge into) and the <strong>compare branch</strong> (your changes)</li>
          <li>Add a title and description, then submit</li>
        </ol>
        <pre><code># Push your feature branch
git push http://alice:token@localhost:3000/alice/myrepo.git feature/my-feature</code></pre>

        <h3>Reviewing diffs</h3>
        <p>Open PRs show a real unified diff of all changes between the base and compare branches. Lines are color-coded: <span style="color:var(--success)">green for additions</span> and <span style="color:var(--danger)">red for deletions</span>.</p>

        <h3>Merging</h3>
        <p>Only the repository owner can merge a pull request. Click <strong>Merge pull request</strong> to perform a <code>git merge</code>. If there are conflicts, the merge will be rejected with an error — resolve conflicts locally and push again.</p>

        <h3>Closing without merging</h3>
        <p>The PR author or repository owner can close a PR without merging by clicking <strong>Close pull request</strong>.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── Pages ── -->
      <section id="pages">
        <h2>Web Hosting (Pages)</h2>
        <p>ForgeLite can serve any repository's <code>gh-pages</code> branch as a static website. No configuration required.</p>

        <h3>Deploy your site</h3>
        <pre><code># Create and switch to gh-pages branch
git checkout -b gh-pages

# Add your HTML/CSS/JS files
echo "&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;h1&gt;My Site&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;" &gt; index.html
git add .
git commit -m "Deploy site"

# Push to ForgeLite
git push http://alice:token@localhost:3000/alice/myrepo.git gh-pages</code></pre>

        <h3>Access your site</h3>
        <p>Your site is immediately available at:</p>
        <pre><code>http://localhost:3000/alice/myrepo/pages/</code></pre>

        <h3>Supported file types</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Extension</th><th>MIME Type</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>.html</code>, <code>.htm</code></td><td><code>text/html</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.css</code></td><td><code>text/css</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.js</code></td><td><code>application/javascript</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.json</code></td><td><code>application/json</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.png</code>, <code>.jpg</code>, <code>.gif</code>, <code>.webp</code></td><td>image/*</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.svg</code></td><td><code>image/svg+xml</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.woff</code>, <code>.woff2</code>, <code>.ttf</code></td><td>font/*</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>.mp4</code>, <code>.webm</code></td><td>video/*</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Directory index</h3>
        <p>Requests to a path without an extension (e.g., <code>/pages/about</code>) automatically try <code>/about/index.html</code> and <code>/about.html</code>.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ── API: Auth ── -->
      <section id="api-auth">
        <h2>API — Authentication</h2>
        <p>All API endpoints return JSON. Authenticated endpoints require a valid session cookie obtained from <code>/api/auth/login</code>, or a <code>Bearer</code> token in the <code>Authorization</code> header.</p>

        <h3>Register</h3>
        <pre><code>POST /api/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "alice",
  "email": "alice@example.com",
  "password": "securepassword"
}

→ 201 { "ok": true, "username": "alice" }</code></pre>

        <h3>Login</h3>
        <pre><code>POST /api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "username": "alice", "password": "securepassword" }

→ 200 { "ok": true }
  Set-Cookie: token=eyJ... (HttpOnly)</code></pre>

        <h3>Logout</h3>
        <pre><code>POST /api/auth/logout
→ 200 { "ok": true }</code></pre>

        <h3>Current user</h3>
        <pre><code>GET /api/auth/me
→ 200 { "id": 1, "username": "alice", "email": "...", ... }</code></pre>

        <h3>Create access token</h3>
        <pre><code>POST /api/auth/tokens
{ "name": "my-laptop" }

→ 200 { "ok": true, "token": "flt_abc123...", "name": "my-laptop" }
  ⚠ Token is shown only once</code></pre>

        <h3>List / delete tokens</h3>
        <pre><code>GET  /api/auth/tokens
DELETE /api/auth/tokens/:id</code></pre>
      </section>

      <!-- ── API: Repos ── -->
      <section id="api-repos">
        <h2>API — Repositories</h2>
